  "slug": "booksmart-bonanza-and-the-best-high-school-movies-with-olivi",
  "title": "'Booksmart' Bonanza and the Best High School Movies, With Olivia Wilde, Beanie Feldstein, and More",
  "show": "The Big Picture",
  "network": "The Ringer",
  "hosts": [
    "Sean Fennessey",
    "Amanda Dobbins"
  ],
  "published": "2019-05-21",
  "runtimeMin": 66,
  "format": "Sean and Amanda praise Olivia Wilde's 'Booksmart,' then each rank their five favorite high school movies. Plus: Sean's South by Southwest interview with the women who made 'Booksmart.'",
  "segments": [
    {
      "kind": "review",
      "heading": "'Booksmart'",
      "note": "Olivia Wilde's directorial debut",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Booksmart",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Two straight-A best friends (Beanie Feldstein and Kaitlyn Dever) realize on the last day of school that the slackers also got into Harvard, and set out to cram four years of partying into one night. Sean and Amanda saw it at South by Southwest and loved it: a Superbad-shaped premise that's its own thing, with the leads never the losers of their own story. Billie Lourd steals scenes as free spirit Gigi; script punched up by Katie Silberman; a hip-hop-heavy soundtrack. Opening against Aladdin on Memorial Day weekend for a wobbly Annapurna."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Amanda's Top 5 High School Movies",
      "note": "counted down 5 to 1",
      "subject": "high school movies",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Clueless",
          "year": 1995,
          "note": "No. 1 - an authentically funny, sophisticated comedy that both mocks Cher and clearly loves her; Amanda saw it too young and had to be taken by her mother."
        },
        {
          "title": "Lady Bird",
          "year": 2017,
          "note": "No. 2 - the one emotional pick, not straight satire; Greta Gerwig nails mother-daughter friction and an honest, sweet view of female friendship."
        },
        {
          "title": "Mean Girls",
          "year": 2004,
          "note": "No. 3 - Tina Fey making the Heathers idea palatable and mainstream, arriving just as the internet turned it into one of the first meme movies."
        },
        {
          "title": "Heathers",
          "year": 1988,
          "note": "No. 4 - the 1988 original that laid bare the politics of female friend groups; too dark and spiky to be made today."
        },
        {
          "title": "Bring It On",
          "year": 2000,
          "note": "No. 5 - of-the-moment cheerleading satire from the TRL era; Kirsten Dunst as an all-time terrible teenager, and an early stab at class and cultural-appropriation dynamics."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "topfive",
      "heading": "Sean's Top 5 High School Movies",
      "note": "counted down 5 to 1",
      "subject": "high school movies",
      "ranked": true,
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Superbad",
          "year": 2007,
          "note": "No. 1 - the most accurate screen portrait of not knowing how to do anything; the Cera-Hill dynamic feels lived-in because Rogen and Goldberg started writing it at 16."
        },
        {
          "title": "Rushmore",
          "year": 1998,
          "note": "No. 2 - against his own better judgment; the Wes Anderson movie he saw at the right age, a sensory confusion of 'you can do this' that logged itself in his head."
        },
        {
          "title": "Scream",
          "year": 1996,
          "note": "No. 3 - radical for a teen who loved horror, comedy, and meta all at once; every layer works without coming at the expense of another."
        },
        {
          "title": "Dazed and Confused",
          "year": 1993,
          "note": "No. 4 - Linklater's gift for casting and one contained night; Randall 'Pink' Floyd as the uniting device that lets the movie bounce figure to figure."
        },
        {
          "title": "Carrie",
          "year": 1976,
          "note": "No. 5 - De Palma's supersized, near-silent-movie evocation of a bad day in high school; a genuine high school movie under the horror."
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "kind": "interview",
      "heading": "The women who made 'Booksmart'",
      "note": "recorded at South by Southwest",
      "guest": "Olivia Wilde, Beanie Feldstein, Kaitlyn Dever, Billie Lourd & Katie Silberman on",
      "films": [
        {
          "title": "Booksmart",
          "year": 2019,
          "note": "Silberman (one of four credited writers) and Wilde wanted smart girls who feel like real people, not a type. Feldstein and Dever lived together through production to build the friendship on screen; a no-sides, everyone-off-book set; Lourd improvised her 4 a.m. scenes."
        },
        {
          "title": "Fast Times at Ridgemont High",
          "year": 1982,
          "note": "The cast watched it together as a touchstone, for the way every ensemble member is fully formed even in a single scene."
        },
        {
          "title": "The Breakfast Club",
          "year": 1985,
          "note": "One of the movies Wilde says she grew up on, and her shorthand for how a high school ensemble lives or dies on chemistry."
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
